 kept in a chamois pouchmelted away faster than hailstones. On the gray eve of poverty, the author,then a self-exiled youth (I transcribe from an old diary), discovered anunexpected patron in the person of Count Starov, a grave old-fashioned Masonwho had graced several great Embassies during a spacious span ofinternational intercourse, and who since 1913 had resided in London. Hespoke his mother tongue with pedantic precision, yet did not spurn rotundfolksy expressions. He had no sense of humor 